Use conditional compilation or the `OnPlatform` pattern in `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

#if ANDROID
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();
#elif IOS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.iOSNotificationService>();
#elif WINDOWS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();
#endif

    return builder.Build();
}
```

**Key points:**

- Place each implementation under `Platforms/<OS>/` so it only compiles for that target (MAUI's default `.csproj` scopes those folders automatically).
- The `#if` directives use symbols defined per target framework (`ANDROID`, `IOS`, `WINDOWS`).
- This won't break on any platform because only the matching branch compiles.

**Alternative — no `#if` needed:** If you put implementations in the platform folders and they all share the same class name, you can use `partial class` or MAUI's `Platforms/` auto-scoping and register once without directives. But the `#if` approach above is the most explicit and common pattern.
